description:
Human papillomavirus 109 (HPV 109) is a member of the Papillomaviridae family, a group of non-enveloped, double-stranded DNA viruses that infect the epithelial cells of various species, including humans. HPV 109 is classified as a high-risk HPV type, meaning it is associated with the development of certain types of cancers, primarily cervical cancer.

The HPV 109 genome is approximately 8,000 base pairs in length and encodes several viral proteins essential for the virus's replication and host cell interactions. These proteins include the early proteins (E1, E2, E4, E5, E6, and E7) and the late proteins (L1 and L2), which play crucial roles in viral DNA replication, gene expression, and virus assembly.

HPV 109 primarily targets the basal layer of the cervical epithelium, where it can establish a persistent infection. Over time, the viral proteins, particularly E6 and E7, can disrupt the normal cell cycle and lead to the development of precancerous lesions and, in some cases, invasive cervical cancer.

Infection with HPV 109 is typically asymptomatic, and the virus can be transmitted through direct skin-to-skin contact or sexual activity. Screening for HPV infections, including HPV 109, is an important part of cervical cancer prevention strategies, as it allows for early detection and appropriate management of precancerous lesions.
